President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed December 15, 2021, as Bill of Rights Day in the United States. He emphasizes the importance of the Bill of Rights in protecting fundamental rights and freedoms and highlights the ongoing commitment to improving and evolving the Constitution. The President acknowledges the historical significance of the Bill of Rights, including its role in abolishing slavery, guaranteeing birthright citizenship, and prohibiting electoral discrimination. He also emphasizes the value of democracy in addressing challenges and encourages respectful disagreement while condemning threats and violence. President Biden references the recent Summit for Democracy, where leaders from around the world came together to address threats to democracies. He calls upon the people of the United States to observe Bill of Rights Day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.